headline: Stocks End Higher After Trump Plays Down Intentions to Fire Powell
summary: A series of reports indicating that President Trump could attempt to fire Federal Reserve Chair  Jerome Powell  sparked a roller-coaster day on Wall Street, before major indexes closed the session near records.  Major stock indexes slid as much as 0.8% midday after news that Trump told Republican lawmakers that he was likely to attempt to remove Powell from his job soon.  The prospect that lower rates would eventually yield higher inflation sparked a selloff in long-dated Treasurys, driving up the 30-year yield around 0.1 percentage point.

headline: Goldman Sachs Profit Surges, Powered by Trading, Investment Banking Revenue
summary: Goldman Sachs  reported a stronger-than-expected profit in the second quarter, fueled by a pickup in dealmaking and surging trading during the market turmoil set off by President Trump’s tariffs.  While heightened trading offset a slower dealmaking environment in the first quarter, big banks saw a bump on both fronts in the second quarter.  Investors continued to reposition their portfolios to adjust for Trump’s trade policy, while bankers and their corporate clients began feeling more comfortable about pursuing mergers and initial public offerings.

headline: Goldman Sachs Tops Earnings Expectations,  Profit Jumps 22%
summary: Goldman Sachs’s second-quarter profit climbed 22% from a year ago to $3.72 billion, the investment bank said Wednesday.  Earnings per share were $10.91, topping Wall Street’s estimates for $9.69, according to analysts’ estimates compiled by FactSet.  Goldman, the sixth-largest bank in the U.S. by assets, said revenue rose 15% from a year ago to $14.58 billion, driven by higher revenue from the global banking and markets business.

headline: Goldman's profit tops estimates as market turbulence powers record equities revenue
summary: (Reuters) -Goldman Sachs' second-quarter profit exceeded Wall Street expectations, as turbulent markets lifted revenue from its equities division to a record and a pickup in dealmaking boosted investment banking.  The results capture a growing trend of market turmoil boosting trading desks across Wall Street as investors rebalance their portfolios to manage tariff-related risks.  Goldman's equities revenue rose 36% to $4.3 billion, higher than the $3.6 billion analysts were expecting, according to estimates compiled by LSEG.
